\section{Drivers of transportation demand}
\label{sec:drivers_of_transportation_demand}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

At the macro scale, 
economic growth is a large driver of demand for transport.
The U.S.\ Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS)
calculates a monthly ``Transportation Services Index'' (TSI),
a weighted and indexed measure of
freight traffic and passenger travel
that measures transportation services output~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Transportation-Bureau-of-Transportation-Statistics:2021uk}.
Figure~\ref{fig:TSI} shows the variation of the TSI over time.
Two patterns emerge:
(a) the general growth of the economy over time drives ever-growing demand for transportation services and
(b) a recession (see 2009) and a pandemic (see 2020) are good ways
to reduce demand for transportation services.
In fact, the correlation between economic growth and freight transportation growth
is so tight that the BTS claims that transport is a good indicator for economic activity
at the macro level~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Transportation-Bureau-of-Transportation-Statistics:2021tn}.

